Command: sselect
Syntax: sselect file.reference {item.list} {selection.criteria} {sort.criteria} {output.specification} {modifiers}{(option)}
Description: The sselect command creates a sorted list of items from the specified file reference that meet selection criteria. The list is a temporary list that is used by the next command as its implicit item list. The list can be permanently saved by the save-list command.

Command: stat
Syntax: stat file.reference {item.list} {selection.criteria} {(options)}
Description: The stat command outputs the total number of items processed and an average value of all items that meet the specified selection criteria.

Command: sum
Syntax: sum file.reference {item.list} attr.name{selection.criteria} {(options)}
Description: The sum command produces a numeric total of a given attribute for all items meeting the optional selection criteria. If an attribute name (attribute name or number) is not specified, the total number of characters in the selected items are calculated.

Modifier: any
Syntax: with {not} any {operator} {"value"}
Description: The any modifier searches an entire item for a match, all attributes and all values. Each value is compared to the selection criteria and if the value passes the criteria, then the item is selected for further processing. This feature is useful for searching nonattribute-oriented files for specific words or phrases, such as word processor documents, source programs, and so on.

Modifier: break-on
Syntax: break-on attr.name{"{text}{'options'}"}
Description: The break-on modifier creates a visual break in output data when the value in the current output field is different from the previous value. The break-on modifier groups items in a listing according to the value of the break-on attribute name. During the list or sort operation, a control-break occurs whenever there is a change in the value of the specified attribute.

Modifier: by
Syntax: by attr.name{by attr.name...}
Description: The by modifier designates a sort key, in ascending order, and must be followed by an attr.name. It may be used with any command that lists or selects items, such as list or select.

Modifier: by-dsnd
Syntax: by-dsnd attr.name{by-dsnd attr.name...}
Description: The by-dsnd modifier designates a sort key, in descending order and must be followed by an attribute name. It may be used with any command that lists or selects items, such as list or select.

Modifier: by-exp-dsnd
Syntax: by-exp-dsnd attr.name{"explosion limiter"}
Description: The explosion limiter specifies that output only occurs on data elements meeting the print limiting criteria. This can be used with any command that lists or selects items, such as list, sort, or select.

Modifier: every
Syntax: with {not} every attr.name{operator} {"value"}
Description: The every modifier forces comparison on every value, rather than any value.

Syntax: if not {each} attr.name{operator} {"value"}
Description: The not operator represents a not equal to condition. This reverses the true sense of the condition in a selection criteria. The #, no, and ne operators perform the same function as not.
Example: list jobs if not stat = "c", list jobs if stat not "c"

Syntax: if not {each} attr.name{operator} {"value"}
Description: The not operator represents a not equal to condition. This reverses the true sense of the condition in a selection criteria. The #, no, and ne operators perform the same function as not.
Example: list jobs if not stat = "c", list jobs if stat not "c"

Syntax: *a n{*a n...}
Description: The number in the item-ID corresponds to the attribute mark that it describes.
Example: list md with *a1 = "d]", list mds,, with a1 = "d]" and with *a8 = "sys]"

Syntax: *a n{*a n...} and an {an...}
Description: The number in the item-ID corresponds to the attribute mark that it describes.
Example: list md with *a1 = "d]", list md with a1 = "d]", list mds,, with a1 = "d]" and with *a8 = "sys]"

Syntax: command dict file.reference {item.list} c/total {(options)}
Description: Displays the total number of frames that make up a binary item. The frame count is divided into two parts, the number frames of: D3 object code, FlashBASIC object code. It is used by AQL and list-obj to add together attributes 3 and 12 of compiled date-time stamps.
Example: list dict bp c/total

Syntax: end {port.number user-ID}
Description: The end command terminates a process on another port, or the current port if a port number is not specified. The end command can also be used to stop a TCL command that was sent to another line by the tcl command, or to terminate a phantom job. The end command clears an active list and requires a sys2 privilege level.
Example: end (ends current process), end 16 dm (stops process on line 16 under user-ID dm)

Syntax: z {h}{s}{d} {tcl.command}
Description: The z command starts a phantom job. Phantom jobs run in the background, meaning that they do not necessarily need a terminal present.
Parameters: h - holds all terminal output in a D3 spooler file hold entry and suppresses output to the terminal; s - suppresses error messages; d - deletes the phantom job item from the jobs file after completion

Syntax: common /ID/variable|array{,variable|array...}
Description: Global common is a named BASIC variable space used to store variables and arrays in the identified area that is only initialized at logon. Global common space is common for all levels of the same process (that is, level pushes, executes, file-time bridges & indexes, and so on).
Example: common /person/ name, company

The abort statement immediately stops program execution and unconditionally returns to the TCL command prompt. The abort statement specifies an abnormal end and can appear anywhere in the program. The abort statement is similar to the stop statement, except the abort statement also terminates execution of any macro or Proc that might have called the program containing the abort statement and aborts the FlashBASIC or BASIC program.
Syntax: abort {message#}{,"parameter"{,"parameter"...}}
abort {error.message.str}

The abort statement immediately stops program execution and unconditionally returns to the TCL command prompt. The abort statement can appear anywhere in the program.
Syntax: abort {message#}{,"parameter"{,"parameter"...}}
abort {error.message.str}
Parameter: message# - Item-ID of the message to output, located in the dm,messages, file. parameter - Values required by the message. If the string form is used, the message string displays on the screen and placed in the dm,messages, file.
Example: open "invoices" to invoice.file else abort 201,"invoices"

The call statement transfers control to an external FlashBASIC or BASIC subroutine and optionally passes a list of arguments to it. Arguments must be separated with a comma. When passing arguments, the same number must occur in the call statement as are declared in the subroutine statement.
Syntax: call cataloged.program.name{(arg{,arg...})}
call @ program.name.var{(arg{,arg...})}
call "file.ref program.name"{(arg{,arg...})}
Example: call process.lines(ID,order.item(1))

The call @ or indirect call form allows the statement to use the subroutine name assigned to a specific variable.
Syntax: call cataloged.program.name{(arg{,arg...})}
call @ program.name.var{(arg{,arg...})}
Examples: Direct call: call process.lines(ID,order.item(1))
Indirect call: program.var = "process.lines"
call @program.var(ID,order.item(1))

The common statement declares data elements to share among different FlashBASIC or BASIC modules. The common statement can be used to share variables between programs and other programs or subroutines.
Syntax: common {/ID/} var{,var...} {,array(dimension1{,dimension2})...}
Example: common x,y,z(10)

The common statement declares data elements to share among different FlashBASIC or BASIC modules. The ID option is used to specify a unique common area called a named common area. Multiple unique named common areas can be declared within the same program module. Named common space is preserved during an entire logon session.
Syntax: common {/ID/} var{,var...}
Example: common /mydata/ name,zip

Syntax: echo {off|on|num.exp}

Description: The echo statement toggles terminal echo on or off. The echo off statement also turns off echo in the FlashBASIC or BASIC debugger.

Parameters: off - Turns terminal echoing off. Characters entered at the terminal are not seen on the screen. on - Turns the normal mode of full duplex echoing on. num.exp - An expression that returns zero is equivalent to echo off. Any other value returned is equivalent to echo on.

Syntax: for var = num.exp1 to num.exp2{step num.exp3} {[while|until] logical.exp}
statement{s}
.
.
next var

Description: The for...next statement is an iterative, incremental loop statement used to repeat a sequence of statements for a specific number of occurrences. A for...next loop executes a set of statements for successive values of a variable until a limiting value is encountered.

Syntax: get var{,length} {setting character.count}
from port.exp{until termination.characters} {returning termination.characters}
{waiting seconds.exp} {then|else statement.block}

Description: The get statement gets raw characters from the specified port. Data read by the get statement is typically echoed unless the program issues an echo off statement.

Syntax: getx var{,length} {setting character.count} 
from port.exp{until termination.characters} {returning termination.characters}
{waiting seconds.exp} {then|else statement.block}

Description: The goto statement transfers control to the location in the FlashBASIC or BASIC program that begins with the given statement label. On statement labels beginning with a nonnumeric value, the : following the statement.label is optional in the goto, but is required following the actual statement label.

Syntax: goto statement.label{:}
go to statement.label{:}

output:
Use the `goto` statement to transfer control to a labeled location in your program. The syntax is:

```
goto statement.label{:}
go to statement.label{:}
```

You can use either `goto` or `go to`. For statement labels that begin with a nonnumeric value, the colon (:) after the label is optional in the goto statement, but it's required after the actual statement label in your code. The program will jump immediately to the specified label and continue execution from that point.

