Syntax: {flash.routine.name:}k{breakpoint.number}

The k (kill) command kills a breakpoint previously set with the b command, and removes the entry from the breakpoint table. The k command, followed by pressing ENTER, removes all breakpoint entries from the table.

Example: *k1 - Kills the first breakpoint in the table.

Syntax: {flash.routine.name:}k{breakpoint.number}

The k (kill) command kills a breakpoint previously set with the b command, and removes the entry from the breakpoint table. The k command, followed by pressing ENTER, removes all breakpoint entries from the table.

Example: *k - Kills all breakpoints.

Syntax: {flash.routine.name:}k{breakpoint.number}

The k (kill) command kills a breakpoint previously set with the b command, and removes the entry from the breakpoint table.

Note: flash.routine.name can only be specified if the program has been optimized through the FlashBASIC compiler. When flash.routine.name is specified, the corresponding debugger command is executed against the specified routine. The colon separating flash.routine.name and the debugger command is required.

Syntax: {flash.routine.name:} t {variable}

The t command places a given variable into the trace table, causing the debugger to display the specified data element along with the contents of the break and trace tables on each break. A plus sign displays for each variable successfully entered into the table, until the table is full. The maximum number of trace table entries is six, except in FlashBASIC, where the number is unlimited.

Example: *tcounter - Sets a trace on the variable called counter.

Syntax: {flash.routine.name:} u {variable}

The u command removes from the trace table a given variable, or all variables, previously specified with the t command. A minus sign displays for each trace table entry successfully removed from the table. The u command, followed by pressing ENTER, clears all trace table entries.

Examples: *uclient.number - removes the trace on client.number variable, *u - removes all traced variables.

Syntax: int _CP_alpha(int* result, CPSTR* string)

The _CP_alpha function is equivalent to the result = alpha(string) BASIC statement. This function returns -1 if an error occurs. The error code is contained in _CP_errno.

Example: CPSTR * s = _CP_mkstr("hi"); int i; _CP_alpha(&i,s); printf("%d\n", i);

Syntax: int _CP_ascii(CPSTR** result, CPSTR* string)

_CP_ascii is equivalent to the result = ascii(string) BASIC statement. This function returns -1 if an error occurs. The error code is contained in _CP_errno.

Example: CPSTR * s = _CP_mkstr("a"); _CP_ascii(&s,s); printf("%c\n",*(_CP_SADDR(s)));

Syntax: int _CP_at1(CPSTR** result, int x)

_CP_at1 is equivalent to the result = @(x) BASIC statement. This function returns -1 if an error occurs. The error code is contained in _CP_errno.

Example: /* clear the screen */ CPSTR * s = _CP_str_null; _CP_at1(&s,-1); _CP_print(s);

Syntax: int _CP_at2(CPSTR** result, int x, int y)

_CP_at2 is equivalent to the result = @(x,y) BASIC statement. This function returns -1 if an error occurs. The error code is contained in _CP_errno.

Example: /* home the cursor */ CPSTR * s = _CP_str_null; _CP_at2(&s,1,1); _CP_print(s);

Syntax: int _CP_break(int expression)

_CP_break is equivalent to the break expression BASIC statement. This function returns -1 if an error occurs. The error code is contained in _CP_errno.

Example: /* turn the break off */ _CP_break(0);

Syntax: int _CP_build_msg(CPSTR * s)

_CP_build_msg queues up arguments for _CP_out_msg. This function, in conjunction with _CP_out_msg, is equivalent to the BASIC error statement. Each parameter is first stacked with _CP_build_msg, and then output with the _CP_out_msg.

Example: CPSTR * s = _CP_mkstr("201"); CPSTR * t = _CP_mkstr("myfile"); _CP_build_msg(s); _CP_build_msg(t); _CP_out_msg();

Example: /* call a user-written routine */
CPSTR * s = _CP_mkstr("hi");
int i = -1;
r = _CP_call(&i,s,0);
if (r < 0)
{
_CP_logoff();
exit(-1);
}
/* Now that the subroutine is loaded, it can be called */
/* very efficiently */
for (j=1; j < 100; j++) _CP_call(&i,s,0);

output:
Here's an example of efficiently calling a user-written routine multiple times:

```c
/* call a user-written routine */
CPSTR * s = _CP_mkstr("hi");
int i = -1;
r = _CP_call(&i,s,0);
if (r < 0)
{
_CP_logoff();
exit(-1);
}
/* Now that the subroutine is loaded, it can be called */
/* very efficiently */
for (j=1; j < 100; j++) _CP_call(&i,s,0);
```

The first call loads the subroutine, and subsequent calls in the loop execute very efficiently since the subroutine is already loaded.

