Example: CPSTR * s = _CP_mkstr("a");
CPSTR * t = _CP_mkstr("A");
int i;

_CP_unix_env();
/* default is casing off - print 0 */
_CP_compare(&i,s,t);
printf("%d\n",i);
/* turn casing on - print 1 */
_CP_casing(1);
_CP_compare(&i,s,t);
printf("%d\n",i);

output:
With casing off (default), strings "a" and "A" are considered equal, so _CP_compare returns 0. When you turn casing on using _CP_casing(1), the same strings are considered different, so _CP_compare returns 1. The example demonstrates this:

```c
/* default is casing off - print 0 */
_CP_compare(&i,s,t);
printf("%d\n",i);  // prints 0
/* turn casing on - print 1 */
_CP_casing(1);
_CP_compare(&i,s,t);
printf("%d\n",i);  // prints 1
```

