Syntax: z {start.col-end.col}

Description: The z command defines zone display limits. The zone display is limited to only the data between the specified beginning and ending column ranges. If both parameters are omitted, the zone function is reset to display the entire line.

Parameters: start.col - Specifies the beginning column range. end.col - Specifies the ending column range.

Syntax: z {start.col-end.col}

Description: The z command defines zone display limits. The zone display is limited to only the data between the specified beginning and ending column ranges. If both parameters are omitted, the zone function is reset to display the entire line.

Example: 014 print customer-ID.z 3-8 (Establishes zone limits) .14 (Go to line14and display) 014 int cu.z (Cancels zone limits)

Syntax: * {text}

Description: The * command treats the entire line following the asterisk as a remark. Any text following the command is ignored by the Output processor.

Example: .*This is comment text.

Syntax: .box {(pos1,pos2{(,pos3,pos4)})}

Description: If position 3 and position 4 are specified, a second box is drawn from column position 3 to column position 4 (position 3 must be greater than position 1, and position 4 must be greater than position 2).

Example: The words Example A and Example B are enclosed in boxes. .box 6,16,43,53 Note: Example A is shown on page n2 and Example B is shown on page n3. .xbox

Syntax: .chapter {text}

Description: The .chapter command starts a new chapter. Chapters start on new pages and the chapter counter is incremented. The literal, Chapter, followed by the optional text, is printed centered between the current margins. The chapter, page number, and text are accumulated for the table of contents.

Example: .chapter Update processor .chapter Output processor produces: Chapter 1 Update processor (page eject) Chapter 2 Output processor

Syntax: .index 'phrase'
.index: 'main.heading' 'phrase' {'phrase'...}
The .index command inserts a phrase and the current page number into the index.

Syntax: .test page {number.lines}

Description: The .test page command tests the number of lines left on the current page and determines whether the text is output on the current or next page.

Parameter: number.lines - If the number of lines specified is less than the count returned, the text following is output on the current page. Otherwise, a page is ejected and the text is output on the new page. This prevents blocks of text from being split across a page boundary.

Syntax: ({dict} file.name {item-ID})
({dict} file.name {item-ID}) {label}
[{dict} {file.name} {item-ID}]
[{dict} file.name{}] {label}

Description: The type of linkage is determined by the character used in the syntax.

Syntax: d{param.num, num.chars|(start.pos, num.chars)}{+}

Description: The d command displays either a specific position from the currently active input buffer, or all the positions.

Parameter: param.num - Specifies the position number in the currently active input buffer. If zero is specified, then all positions in the buffer display. If no position number is specified, then the current position of the buffer pointer is used.

Syntax:
celement{;element...}
celement{/*}
celement{xelement}{...}

The c processing code concatenates elements for output. Each element may be delimited by a character to appear on output. The elements can be: Numeric constants, An attribute position, An alphanumeric character string enclosed in quotation marks.

The asterisk is a special character used to concatenate the resulting value from the last processing code operation.

display statement
Syntax: display message.text{+}
The display statement outputs text on the screen in a macros or a Procs. If the message text is terminated by a +, the trailing carriage return is suppressed.

prompt statement
Syntax: prompt {prompt.text}
The prompt statement in a macro prompts the user with a specified text string. The user is then given the option to either continue (by entering c, or stopping the process (by entering q). No other characters are allowed.

abs.fid command
Syntax: abs.fid {file.reference}
The abs.fid command displays the ABS information. The ABS base FID, release date, implementation, and release title display.

account-restore command
Syntax: account-restore account.name{(options)}
The account-restore BASIC program restores an account from an account-save, file-save, or md-save magnetic media or pseudo tape. Options include: a=tape already positioned, b=ignore indexes on tape, c=compatible tape, d=data-sensitive files, f=disable fast restores, g=suppress index generation, m=Microdata compatibility, n=disable file reallocation, s=suppress transaction log messages, w=byte-swapped machine restore, z=bypass incremental/transaction log prompts.

account-save command
Syntax: account-save {account.name} {account.name...} {(options)}
Options include: l=save only listed item-IDs, m=same as l but clears dirty bits, r=same as l and m but saves list with file. The l option saves only the list of item-IDs provided in the associated item for the given file, located in the dm,file of files, file, beginning at attribute 25.

alarm command
Syntax: alarm {delay|hh:mm{:ss}{,date|*}{command}}{(options}
The alarm BASIC program schedules a task at a given time, or after a given delay in seconds, at a given date. Options: c=cancel all alarms, l=list current alarms, s=set current alarms.

archive-accounts command
Syntax: archive-accounts {<purge_date>} {(d}
The archive-accounts command moves entries from the accounts data level to an archive data level, or optionally deletes them. The (d) option specifies that entries will be deleted instead of archived.

assignfq (UNIX) command
Syntax: assignfq form.queue{-n},device.name{(unix.command)} {,form.queue,device.name{(unix.command)} {...}} {(options}
The assignfq command assigns a printer device driver to a spooler form queue. On UNIX-based implementations, the spooler can transfer data directly to a UNIX-based operation by placing the UNIX command string in parentheses after the device name.

auto-disconnect command
Syntax: auto-disconnect [(n[-m])] {delay time} {(C}
The auto-disconnect command allows certain clients the capability to disconnect from the server with a custom delay, reserving the line for reconnect. The delay allows clients to reserve their connection while logged off, releasing the license for other users.

auto-restart command
Syntax: AUTO-RESTART [ UPDATE.USER | [n[-m]] | PERMANENT ] { command | CLEAR }
The auto-restart command allows the user to specify or clear a command that is executed whenever a D3 process is attempting to go to TCL. Unless the n option is specified, changes take effect on the next log on.

check-ws {port.number}

The check-ws BASIC program validates the integrity of the workspace for a given port. If successful, displays: 0000 00
where 0000 is workspace status and 00 is level.

chg-device device.number option=value {option=value...}

The chg-device command changes a tape device. Changes made are not permanent and are lost when the virtual machine is rebooted.
For Windows: Not Supported

clear-file {(}{data} file.reference{,file.reference}) {(options}
clear-file {(}dict file.reference){(options}

Clears the dictionary or data section of specified file of all items and retains the primary file space area. To clear dictionary section, 'dict' must be specified before file reference. If dictionary is specified, file-defining items (D-pointers) are not cleared.

clear-index file.reference a.code{(options)}

a.code - Specifies the a processing code used in forming index keys. Must include attribute number immediately after the 'a'.
c - Specifies a case sensitive index. Default is case insensitive.

clear-locks {host}{(options}

f{fid} - Clears all group and item locks for a specific frame-ID, specified as decimal number
The f option indicates the number immediately following it is a frame-ID. Without the f option, the number is interpreted as a port number.

compile file.reference itemlist* {(options}

o - Produces a FlashBASIC optimized code
Warning: Compilation with the (o flag might take a long time to compile and tends to use a great deal of the machine's resources.

conv-case file.reference itemlist*{(options)}

e - Used with q option to convert case of items within quotation marks due to chain, tcl, and execute statements
q - Leaves text within quotation marks unchanged

copy file.reference itemlist*{(options)}
to: {(file.reference} {itemlist}

Options:
o - Overwrites existing items when duplicate item-IDs exist
u - If item-ID exists in destination, creates new item-ID by concatenating original with letter starting with lowercase 'a'

copy-list {{file.reference} {itemlist*} {(options}
to: {(file.reference} {itemlist}

A file reference may be specified because any file can hold lists. The copy command may also be used, but copy-list defaults to the pointer-file.

Syntax: cp file.reference itemlist*{(options}
The cp BASIC program copies the specified items to the printer via the spooler.
Options: n-Integer number that specifies the number of items to copy, a-Activates assembly list format, f-Outputs a form feed between each item, s-Suppresses display of line numbers, x-Outputs in hexadecimal.

cp command - copies specified items to the printer via the spooler
ct command - invokes the copy command and copies the specified items to the terminal
Both use similar syntax: file.reference itemlist* {(options)}

Syntax: create-file file.reference dict.modulo data.modulo{(options)}
First form creates a new file with both data and dictionary sections.
Example: create-file customers 7 101

Command: encrypt-file
Syntax: encrypt-file filename{,data-file}{(options}
Description: The encrypt-file command encrypts data in a specified file. If this command is run on a system without OpenSSL, the current process will stop and return to TCL. Additionally, you will see the Encryption libraries are not loaded message. Encryption does not affect any existing file translates, indexes, bridges, triggers, and so on. These features will continue to function as expected. However, note that read and write operations on encrypted files are significantly slower than read and write operations on unencrypted files.

Command: end
Syntax: end {port.number user-ID}
Description: The end command terminates a process on another port, or the current port if a port number is not specified. The end command stops processing at the previous level and returns to the preceding level TCL prompt. However, if there is an active list at the current level, then list is cleared, and control is returned to the previous level. The end command can also be used to stop a TCL command that was sent to another line by the tcl command, or to terminate a phantom job.

Command: environ
Syntax: environ {-x} {-n} {-c string|-f {file.reference} item-ID}
Description: The environ command manipulates the UNIX shell environment variables from TCL. Commands can be passed from the TCL command line or from an item. It is possible to set and test shell variables, and execute TCL commands (including UNIX commands, prefixed by an exclamation point) under control of the shell variables.

Command: file-save
Syntax: file-save {(options}
Description: The file-save command in the DM account invokes the procedure to perform a full backup of each file in the D3 file system. File statistics are built with each save, including an account-save and a dummy save, contrary to VME file statistics.

Command: find
Syntax: find {file.reference} {(options}
Description: The find BASIC program searches a file for the existence of one or more strings of characters in any attribute, and optionally creates and saves a list. The file reference can be specified on the command line. Otherwise, the program requests it. Next, the search strings are requested by the program. Enter the strings without any enclosing delimiters. The system repeatedly asks for additional search strings.

list-errors syntax: list-errors {(options}
Description: The list-errors macro produces a sorted report of the error messages logged into the dm,errors, file, beginning with the most recently logged message.

list-aborts syntax: list-aborts {(options}
Description: The list-aborts command produces a sorted report of the aborts logged into the dm,errors, file, beginning with the most recently logged message. It is different from the list-errors macro in that it only displays aborts not informational messages (such as logoffs or system boots).

Syntax: listc file.reference {select.list}{heading"heading text"}{(n}

Description: The listc BASIC program invokes the list-label BASIC program to produce a columnar display of the item-IDs in the specified file, in the order of appearance in the file.

Parameters: n - Number of columns - 4 default; 6 maximum. Any valid selection criteria can be passed through to AQL for processing.

Syntax: listconn {file.reference} {(options}

Description: The listconn BASIC program produces a report of all items defined as connectives (also called modifiers) in the specified file reference. Any item in the master dictionary with the letter c as the first character in attribute 1 is a connective. The items in the report are sorted by the value of attribute 1.

Parameters: n - Affects output to the terminal only, preventing output from pausing at the end of each (terminal) page of output. p - Directs output to the system printer, via the spooler.

Syntax: listfiles {file.reference} {(options}

Description: The listfiles BASIC program produces a report showing all file-defining items and synonym-defining items in an optionally specified file name or account name. The default file name is md.

Parameters: n - Affects output to the terminal only, preventing output from pausing at the end of each (terminal) page of output. p - Directs output to the system printer, via the spooler.

Syntax: listprocs {account.name} {(options}

Description: The listprocs BASIC program produces a sorted report of all items defined as Procs in the specified file name. The default file name is md when none is specified.

Parameters: n - Affects output to the terminal only, preventing output from pausing at the end of each (terminal) page of output. p - Directs output to the system printer, via the spooler.

Syntax: logoff {port.number}{(options}

Description: The logoff BASIC program terminates a process on a given port and sends the port to the logon prompt. The logoff process first attempts a normal log off by simulating a break and off sequence on the target port. If that times out, logoff escalates and forces the process into the debugger and simulates an off. If that fails, the target port is reinitialized without attempting to clean up or recover its workspace.

Warning: Logging off a port should be treated as a last resort. It should be used by a system administrator only when the status of the PIB and potential problems that could arise have been assessed.

Syntax: logon {(p)}
line,user-ID,user-password,md,md-password:

Description: The logon command logs on a port, other than the one currently being used, onto a specific account. The (p option starts process as a phantom line - this requires an existing unused port and suppresses the logon sequence (time/date display, welcome message, acc file update).

Syntax: mload file.reference itemlist* {(options)}

Description: The mload command loads the assembled object code into the virtual memory address defined in the routine. For Windows: Not Supported

Parameters: n - Returns the item checksum data without actually loading the item. v - Verifies mismatches and errors only.

Command: paint
Syntax: paint file.reference {item.list*}{attr.list}{(options}
Description: The paint command displays items to the screen or printer in Update processor format. The paint command behaves differently than an AQL list command, in that controlling/dependent attributes are displayed as columns and rows. Also, attribute headers are boldfaced.

Command: paint
Syntax: paint file.reference {item.list*}{attr.list}{(options}
Parameters: attr.list - Indicates the names of the attributes that are affected by the command. Specific attributes can display, without using the default macro defined on the file's D-pointer. This option functions in the same way as the outlist in a list or sort command.

Command: pid
Syntax: pid {port.number} {(options}
Description: The pid BASIC program displays the UNIX PID of a D3 process. The first form displays the UNIX PID or the specified D3 port number (PIB). For Windows: Not Supported

Command: pid
Syntax: pid * {pid.to.search} {(options}
Description: The second form displays the UNIX PIDs of all the D3 processes currently connected to the virtual machine. If a list of PIDs to search is provided, a plus sign displays before each process found in the list. This form is useful to determine whether a specified UNIX process, identified by its PID, is connected to the virtual machine.

Command: power-off
Syntax: power-off {(u}
Description: The power-off command in the DM account brings the system to an orderly shutdown by logging off all users, flushing memory to disk, and parking the disk heads prior to halting the system. If the port is not logged off by the time the power-off reaches its final phase, the port is automatically logged off.

Command: qselect
Syntax: qselect file.reference {itemlist*} {(attribute.number)}
Description: The qselect command creates a list from the specified file reference and item list, similar to the get-list command. The list is constructed from the attributes identified by the attribute number in an item (or list of items) specified by the item list. Each attribute, value, and sub-value becomes a single attribute value in the list.

Command: :reset-async
Syntax: :reset-async {port.number}
Description: The :reset-async BASIC program resets the current port or all ports to default values. For Windows: Not Supported. If the port number is omitted, all ports are reset. The default values are: converse, tandem, and mirror, all off, yet enabled for use.

Syntax: reset-port port.number{(options}
reset-port tty.name{(options}

Description: The reset-port BASIC program restarts suspended output and drains both the input and output terminal buffers. For Windows: Not Supported

output:
Yes, you can restart suspended output using the reset-port command. The syntax is:

reset-port port.number{(options}
reset-port tty.name{(options}

This command restarts suspended output and drains both input and output terminal buffers. Note that this command is not supported on Windows systems.

