Command: where
Syntax: where {port.number{-port.number}} {user-ID} {(options)}
Options: a - Displays a character next to the PIBs information to indicate license consumption type, h - Suppresses the heading, l - Shows the status for each pushed level, n - No pause option suppresses the pause at the end of the page, o - Shows information only for those PIBs that have specified settings when used with the 'a' option, p - Directs output to the system printer via spooler, u - Returns the user tally under the Stat column heading, z - Displays where status for all ports including inactive ports.

Command: where
Syntax: where {port.number{-port.number}} {user-ID} {(options)}
Examples: where 'dm' - provides the status of those ports that are currently logged into the dm user-ID. where 13-22 - provides the status of port numbers 13 through 22. where (z - provides the status of all port numbers. where (a - shows the where (a) report of direct connected lines using Connection Pool licenses.

Command: wincopy
Syntax: WINCOPY {filename} {item.list} {(options)} TO:{(filename} {item.list}
Description: The wincopy command is a modified version of the copy command that copies items between D3 and the Windows file system. The wincopy command allows items in a D3 file to be copied to a Windows directory or to copy files from a Windows directory to a D3 file. Attribute marks in the D3 data are converted to Windows end-of-line markers (crlf) when copying to Windows and Windows end-of-line markers (crlf) are converted to attribute marks when copying from Windows to D3.
